MINNESOTA STATE NOTIFICATION NUMBER CALLED AND INCIDENT REPORTED TO JOE #38.

column168: AFTER PACKAGE AND OTHER PACKAGES THE LEAKER SPILLED ON WERE CONTAINED AND BROUGHT TO PSC DAMAGE AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH MALLINCKRODT DISPOSAL STEPS AND FILLED OUT A D/R ON IT. [**RON HINKLE NEVER RESPONDED TO NUMEROUS PHONE CALLS - DATE ENTERED AS 11/01/1993**]
DAMAGE DISCOVERED DURING UNLOADING.  PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER DAMAGE.

80 STEEL DRUMS OF PRODUCT WAS LOADED INTO TRAILER AND STRAPPED IN WITH LOAD STRAP.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DRUMS REBBED AGAINST ONE ANOTHER CAUSING A PIN HOLE TO DEVELOPE IN ONE.  LEAK DISCOVERED BY ODOR AND BY THE DRIVER WHEN STOPPING FOR BREAK.  SMELL AND LEAKED CONTAINED IN TRIALER. UNLOADED/RELOADED, CLEANUP BY OHM OF HOUSTON, TX.  LEAKING DRUM OVERPACKED.  LEAD BARRELS TIGHTER TOGETHER MAY HELP - BUT ROUGH ROADS IN LA ALSO CONTRIBUTED.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: WHEN DRIVER CHECKED THE LOAD AT OUR TERMINAL, ONE DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A SMALL PINHOLE ON THE SIDE FROM CORROSION OF THE METAL.  THREE CUPS OF LUQID HAD SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRIALER AROUND THE DRUM.  DRIVER OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND PLACED ALL RESIDUE FROM THE SPILL IN THE OVERPACK WITH THE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AT ENSCO INC.

THE LEAK FROM THE SEAM WAS NOTICED WHEN THE FORK-LIFT WAS ATTEMPTING TO TRANSPORT THE DRUM TO THE TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT.  APPROX. 8 OZ OF THE CONTENTS LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINER.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL PLACED IN THE DRUM TO ABSORB THE SILL.  THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE SPILL IS AN IMPERVOUS URETHANE COATING OVER CONCRETE WHICH WAS WIPED DRY USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE AREA WAS THEN MOPPED TO REMOVE THE REMINING RESIDUE AND THE WATER INSATE AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE THEN DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE SAFETY KLEEN NEW CASTELE, KY., RECYCLE CENTER.

column168: DRIVER OPENED THE DOORS AT THE SECOND PICK-UP POINT AND DISCOVERED A STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE LOAD REVEALED ONE OF THE LIDS ON THE PORTABLE TANKS HAD POPPED OFF.  FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE OPENING ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  DRIVER WAS ABLE TO RESECURE THE LID AND ABSORBED ALL SPILLED LIQUID WITH OIL DRY.  ALL RESIDUE FORM THE SPILL WAS DISPOSED OF AT SYSTECH ENVIRONMENTAL AND THE TRAILER WASHED THOROUGHTLY BEFORE RELOAD.

AS DRIVER ARRIVED AT TEXAS A&M POWER PLANT, JUST BEFORE HE GOT THERE, HE DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  HE STOPPED IMMEDIATELY AND FOUND ALL 4 BOLTS HAD WORKED LOOSE AT THE 2" BALL VALVE.  HE TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND STOPPED LEAK.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEANED UP SPILLED PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY THE PRODUCT HAD JUST STARTED LEAKING WHEN DRIVER DISCOVERED IT.
CARTON WAS DISCOVERED LOADED UPSIDE DOWN.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART LEAKED FROM CAP.
IT APPEARS THAT ONE ONE GALLON CAN WAS PACKAGED FROM THE SHIPPER WITH A HOLE IN THE TOP OF IT.

THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  A CERTIFIED RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED BY THE SHIPPER TO THE SCENE.  THE RESPONSE TEAM PROPERLY RECOOPERED THE TOTE TANK.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARD TO DESTINATION.

THE BAGS WERE ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY AND PROPERLY RECOOPERED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

THE DRIVER FOUND A STEEL DRUM LEAKING AT THE CONSIGNEE DOCK.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE TRAILER WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE AND THE SHIPMENT REMAINED WITH THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: THE PACKAGE HAD OBVIOUSLY BEEN DROPPED AND CAN WAS DENTED, HOWEVER THE PACKAGE STILL NEEDED EXTRAS, CUSHIONING AND ABOUT 200-300 BURSTING TEXT BOX. SPILL WAS PROCESSED FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURES.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THIS LOCATION THE DRIVER WAS TOLD THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT AS ORDERED. THIS IS A PUMP LOCATION AND THERE IS NO GAUGE ON THIS ABOVE GROUND TANK. ALL THE DRIVER COULD DO IS TO TAKE THEIR WORD THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT. WHEN THE DRIVER STILL HAD ABOUT 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO PUMP, THE PRODUCT STARTED COMING OUT THE VENT PIPE AT THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE DIKE AREA. OUR TERMINAL MANAGER CALLED AND SPOKE WITH THE PLANT FOREMAN AT FLORIDA MINING AND HE SAID THE SPILL WAS THE FAULT OF FLORIDA MINING AND THEY WOULD BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE CLEAN UP THEMSELVES.

THE LID WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING, I PUT THE REMAINING LIQUID IN A NEW CONTAINER AND SENT IT BACK, FILLED OUT A DAMAGE INSPECTION REPORT, BAGGED AND SEALED THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL, THEN FAXED THE INFORMATION TO MALLINCKDORT.  AWAITING ANSWER FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: OUR LAIDLAW DRIVER PICKED UP FOUR WRANGLERS WHICH APPEARED TO BE STABLE. THE MATERIAL WAS MANIFESTED AS A SOLID, CLASS 9.  WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED HIS NEXT STOP HE NOTICED LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  PUTTY AND DUCT TAPE WAS USED TO COVER THE HOLE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A LEAKPROOF TRUCK.  THE DRIVER CLEANED UP SPILL WITH SPEEDI DRY AND ABSORBANT PIGS WHICH THEN GOT PACKED INTO THE WRANGLER.  HE THEN RETURNED THE LEAKING CONTAINER TO THE GENERATOR.  LAIDLAW NORTH EAST HAS INSTRUCTED IT'S DRIVERS TO INSPECT CONTAINERS MORE THOROUGHLY FOR DEFECTS AND FOR LIQUID THAT MAY BE IN WRANGLERS.  IN THE FUTURE, ANY WRANGLER THAT OBVIOUSLY CONTAINS LIQUID WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

THE PRODUCT HAD SETTLED IN TRANSIT CAUSING THE LIQUID TO COME TO THE TOP.  THE LIQUID CAUSED THE FIBER BOX TO WEAKEN AND SPLIT.  SHIPPER SENT A CREW TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL AND OVERPACK THE CONTAINER.  ALL WASTE ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER.

CUSTOMER ORDERED 2200 GAL. KEROSENE.  DISPATCH ERROR CAUSED DRIVER TO LOAD 7800 GAL.  THIS LOCATION IS A SMALL TANK FARM WITH ABOVE GROUND TANKS. THERE IS NO WAY FOR A DRIVER TO KNOW WHICH TANK IS BEING FILLED AND HOW MUCH IS IN THE TANK.  THE DRIVER ASKED MANAGEMENT PRIOR TO UNLOADING IF THEY WERE SURE IT WOULD FIT.  THE CUSTOMER, BELIEVING THAT HE HAD 2200 GAL. SAID THAT IT WOULD.  APPROXIMATELY 70 GAL. SPRAYED OUT OF THE VENT PIPE BEFORE OUR DRIVER WAS AWARE OF THE PROBLEM AND ABLE TO SHUT IT DOWN.
WHILE DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK ABOUT ONE GALLON OF HEATING OIL LEAKED OUT OF FILL AND VENT.  THE SPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED UP.

THE INNER POLY LINING OF THE BOX WAS TORN AND APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF POWDERED WASTE HAD SPILLED INTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. COMPANY PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO UTILIZE SHOP VACUUMS, BROOMS AND SHOVELS AND OVERPACK THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND THE REMAINDER OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BAG.  ALL EQUIPMENT UTILIZED TO CLEAN THE SPILL WILL GO TO THE RECEIVER FOR DISPOSAL ALONG WITH THE WASTE.  THE TRAILER WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED AFTER ALL CARGO WAS REMOVED.

DRIVER ERRORED WHEN HE FAILED TO FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURES IN "SETTING THE PLANT" DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  AT THIS AFORE MENTIONED DESTINATION. DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO WRONG TANK BECAUSE TANKS WERE IMPROPERLY MARKED. TANK OVER-CAPACITATED, AND DRIVER DISCONTINUED THE DELIVERY IMMEDIATELY. DRIVER REPORTED PROPERLY AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED.  MITIGATION OF THE INCIDENT RESULTED, AND CLEAN-UP WAS ORDERED.  SITE WAS SURFACE REMEDIATED AND CONTAMINANTS WERE RECOVERED. DRIVER WAS REVIEWED FOR HIS ACTIONS AND RETRAINED ON PROCEDURES.

DRIVER ERRANTLY LEFT HIS POSITION AT THE NOZZEL END WHILE REFUELING HIS UNIT.  PUMP NOZZEL VIBRATED OUT OF THE FUEL TANK ON THE TRACTOR. DRIVER FURTHER REPORTS THAT HE HAD SECURED THE NOZZEL AGAINST FALLING OUT. SECURING PREVENTED NOZZEL FROM HITTING THE GROUND, WHICH WOULD HAVE SHUT IT OFF.  DRIVER WILL RECEIVE WARNING LETTER AND A FORMAL REVIEW OF HIS SKILL LEVEL.

column17: P B & S CHEMICAL CO INC
column25: P B & S CHEMICAL CO INC
column168: CARGO TANKER 64903 WAS LOADED WITH 46,330 LBS. OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION AT OUR NITRO, WV FACILITY AT 12:15 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 8, 1993. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT ARISTECH CHEMICAL IN HAVERHILL, OHIO AT 13:45 HOURS ON THIS DATE.  OUR CUSTOMER'S WEIGHT TICKET INDICATED UNLOADING 46,400 LBS. OF PRODUCT. THE OHIO DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION-MAINTENANCE SECTION INVESTIAGATED A WHITE RESIDUE ON THE PAVEMENT OF U.S. ROUTE 52 IN FRONT OF THE ARISTECH FACILITY AND REPORTED TO THE OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTIONAL AGENCY.  THE OHIO-EPA REPORTEDLY SOUGHT ASSISTANCE FROM ARISTECH CHEMICAL IN THE IDENTIFICATION OF THE WHITE RESIDUE.  WE WERE CONTACTED THE AFTERNOON OF NOVEMBER 9TH BY ARISTECH CHEMICAL CONCERNING THIS MATTER.  P.B. & S. CHEMICAL'S ST. ALBANS- KVC HAZMAT TEAM NEUTRALIZED THE DEPOSITS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE BY USING DILUTE PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION APPLIED BY A WAREHOUSE FLOOR SCRUBBER.  IN OUR INVESTIAGION WE ASCERTAINED POSSIBLE PRODUCT SPILLAGE WAS FROM A PRODUCT UNLOAD HOSE BEING STORED IN THE HOSE STORAGE- BIN ON THE CARGO TANKER.  THE STORAGE-BIN HAS A DRAIN- OPENING 1 TUBE FOR RAIN WATER DRAINAGE. TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE ALL PRODUCT UNLOAD HOSE (S) SHALL BE DRAINED PRIOR TO BEING PLACED IN THE HOSE STORAGE- BIN ON THE CARGO TANKER.

HE ALSO DEPLOYED SPILL KIT MATERIAL AND REPORTED IMMEDIATELY. AN EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED AND THE INCIDENT WAS MITIGATED.  SITE WAS DECLARED OKAY.  THE DRIVER WILL BE REVIEWED FOR POSSIBLE RE-TRAINING.

column168: THE SHELL DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE STATION AT ROUGHLY 6PM ON NOVEMBER 15TH, 1993.  DUE TO HEAVY TRAFFIC FLOW THE DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO USE AND ALTERNATE STATION ENTRY. WHILE MANEUVERING THE TRUCK ON THE STATION PROPERTY, THE LOADING AND UNLOADING VALVES CAME INTO CONTACT WITH A RAISED PUMP ISLAND PROTECTOR.  THE CONTACT SHEARED OFF THE TRAILER'S COMPARTMENT #1 AND #2 DROP VALVES.  ONLY THE #1 COMPARTMENT LEAKED AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT.  THE DRIVER PERFORMED THE FOLLOWING IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING HE IMPACT: 1) REQUESTED CUSTOMER TO NOTIFY ATTENDANT IN STATION OF SITUATION AND TOLD HER TO CALL FIRE DEPARTMENT, 2) CLEARED THE AREA PUMP ISLANDS, 3) SHUT OFF ALL POWER TO THE UNIT, AND 4) NOTIFIED SHELL'S CENTRAL DISPATCH & CARGO PLANT RESPONSE ACTION TEAM 5) MADE AN INITIAL ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK AND STOP THE FUEL FLOW FROM #1.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND ASSISTED IN THE PLUGGING OF THE LEAK.  THEY FOAMED THE AREA AND BUILT SAND BURMS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL ON THE IMPERMEABLE SURFACE UNTIL THE RESPONSE ACTION TEAM ARRIVED.  SHELL'S RESPONSE ACTION TEAM WORKED CLOSELY WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PUMPED OFF THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER INTO A VACUUM TRAILER AND COLLECTED THE CONTAINED PRODUCT IN THE BURMED AREA.  BASED ON THE SERVICE STATION TANK GAUGES AND THE VOLUME OF RETURNED PRODUCT, THE TOTAL LOSS FROM THE INCIDENT IS ESTIMATED AT 300 GALLONS.   CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1) THE ONGOING CORRECTIVE ACTION INVOLVES A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT WITH ALL DRIVERS, STRESSING THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFE MANEUVERING, AND PROPER BACKING PROTOCOL.  2) MONTHLY INTERNAL VALVE CHECK PROCESS HAS BEEN REVISED/RE-STRESSED TO INCLUDE A REVIEW BY SHELL'S DELIVER SUPERVISOR AND THE SHELL'S MAINTENANCE COMPANY.  3) MODIFICATION OF THE NUMBER AND LOCATION OF FIXED OBJECTS ON THE SITE ARE UNDER REVIEW FOR POSSIBLE CHANGES WHICH WOULD IMPROVE THE ABILITY A TRUCK TO MANEUVER WHILE ON SITE. PLEASE CONTACT ME @ (708) 572-5803 IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS.  JAMES C KEUPER, JR.-PLANT SUPERINTENDENT.

SINCE THERE WERE NO MARKINGS. LABELING OR A DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS THE SHIPPER WAS ASKED TO PROVIDE THE MATERIALS FLASH POINT. THE SHIPPER SAID THAT IT WAS GREATER THAT 100 F BUT NOT MORE THAN 137 F.  I NOTIFIED THE NORTHWEST MOUNTAIN FAA DUTY OFFICER ON 11 11 93. TOM STOVALL, FAA ASKED ME TO GET PICTURES TAKEN ON THE PACKAGE AND CONTENTS. THIS EVIDENCE IS BEING FORWARDED TO THE FAA IN RENTON, WA.

ON NOVEMBER 1, 1993 TWO DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED ON SITE AT OVERNITE TRANSPORTATION CO. 342 STOKES PARK RD. BETHLEHEM, PA18017. TWO DRUMS CONTAINING 55 GALLONS EACH COMPLETELY SPILLED CONTAMINATING ALL FREIGHT INSIDE TRAILER. CALLED ON SITE WAS REACT ENVIRONMENTAL. REACT WAS IN CHARGE OF CLEAN UP INVOLVING DESTRUCTION OF SOME 39 CARTONS OF MATERIAL. NO INJURIES ON SITE.

ON NOVEMBER 15, 1993, OUR VEHICLE WAS ENROUTE TO PORT ARANSAS, TX. SAME AS REMARKS FOR REPORT A. SOUTHBOUND ON US 59 APPROXIMATELY 4.5 MILES SOUTH OF GANADO, TX. WHEN THE DRIVER SAW A GLOW ON THE RIGHT REAR AXLE OF THE SEMI-TRAILER. THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY TO INVESTIGATE THE GLOW. THE RIGHT REAR AXLE OF THE SEMI-TRAILER HAD CAUGHT FIRE. THE DRIVER THEN DISCONNECTED HIS TRUCK FROM THE SEMI-TRAILER AND DROVE IT TO A SAFE AREA. THE SEMI-TRAILER THEN PARTIALLY BURNED. DURING THE FIRE, THREE ACETYLENE BOTTLE'S FUSIBLE METAL RELIEF VALVES RELEASED THE BOTTLE'S CONTENTS AND A FOURTH ACETYLENE BOTTLE RUPTURED (APPROXIMATELY 76 LBS. OF ACETYLENE GAS TOTAL IN THE FOUR BOTTLES). ALSO, TWELVE OXYGEN BOTTLES RELEASED THEIR CONTENT DURING THE FIRE (APPROXIMATELY 336 LBS. OF OXYGEN). THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE FIRE CANNOT BE DETERMINED DUE TO THE EXTENSIVE FIRE DAMAGE TO THE RIGHT REAR AXLE WHERE THE FIRE STARTED BUT OUT INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE PROBABLE CAUSE WAS AN OIL SEAL ON THE RIGHT REAR AXLE. WHEN THE OIL SEAL WENT OUT THE LUBRICATING OIL WAS THROWN OUT ONTO THE TIRES AND THE RESULTING HEAT FROM THE LACK OF LUBRICANT CAUSED THE FIRE TO START. OUR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT HAS INCREASED INSPECTIONS OF THIS AREA TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURENCES. ALL AND/OR PART OF US 59 IN THIS AREA WAS CLOSED FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME. THE CITY OF EDNA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE FIRE AND DID A COMMENDABLE JOB OF CONTROLLING THE FIRE AND PROTECTING LIVES AND PROPERTY. THERE WERE NO INJURIES DUE TO THE INCIDENT. THE SEMI-TRAILER AND ITS LOAD INCLUDING THE BURNT BOTTLES WERE REMOVED TO ALLEN'S WRECKER SERVICE IN VICTORIA, TX. AND SUBSEQUENTLY HAVE BEEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR FACILITY.

column168: ON 11/22/93 AT 14:15 IT WAS REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKING FROM ONE OF RT'S VANS IN THE RPTS TRANSFER STATION. APPRORIATE PERSONNEL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY BY MOVING THE VAN ONTO CONTAINMENT AT THE PROCESS DOCK. RIS PERSONNEL PROCESSED THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND CLEANED UP THE VISUALLY CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL AND PLACED IT INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM FOR PROCESSING BY RIS. THE CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND REMINDED THAT ONLY SOLIDS ARE APPROPRIATED FOR THE GAYLORD CONTAINERS. WE REVIEWED WITH THE RTS DRIVERS DOT AND RIS GAYLORD CONDITION REQUIREMENTS FOR WHICH EACH GAYLORD IS TO BE INSPECTED PRIOR TO BE LOADING.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO TURN EXTERNAL VALVE SO HE ASSUMED IT WAS CLOSED. WHEN HE BEGAN TO PUMP THE PRODUCT, IT SPRAYED OUT OF THE EXTERNAL VALVE ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE INTERNAL VALVE. THE HOSES WERE NOT AT THAT POINT CONNECTED AS THE CUSTOMER NEEDED TO SAMPLE THE PRODUCT. ONCE THE SAMPLING WAS DONE, THE HOSES WERE CONNECTED AND THE PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED WITH THE VALVE PARTIALLY OPENED. HOWEVER, WHEN THE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED, THE VALVE WHICH WAS BY THEN WARM, WAS CLOSED WITH NO DIFFICULTY. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND REPORTED TO CHEMTREC BY OUR DRIVER AND THE CUSTOMER DISPATCHER. OUT VALVE IS BEING COMPLETELY INSPECTED AND CLEANED.
SHIPPER'S EMPLOYEE PROCEEDED TO LOAD TANK WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS ON THE PHONE. INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES WERE NOT CLOSED AND PRODUCT WAS LOST. SPILL WAS CLEANED BY THE SHIPPER.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THE UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER; THE UNLOADER REMOVED THE VACCUUM BREAKER FLANGE AND INADVERTENTLY OPENED THE VALVE RESULTING IN THE PRODUCT SPRAYING OUT. THE UNLOADER SHUT THE VALVE AND PROCEEDED TO SHOWER AREA. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY THE CONSIGNEE.
TANK BACKED INTO A EPA CLEAN UP SITE TO BE LOADED BY RUST REMEDIATION SERVICE. THE INTERNAL VALVE, HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED, PRIOR TO LOADING CAUSING ON SITE SPILL.

CARGO TANK DEVELOPED A LEAK WHILE IN ROUTE TO RICHMOND, KY. UNIT WAS PARKED IN A VACANT STONE LOT OFF OF HIGHWAY 58. DRIVER NOTICED LEAK WHILE PERFORMING PRE-TRIP. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE DRIPPING LIQUID USING A 5 GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET. PLASTIC SHEETING AND ABSORBENT SPILL PADS WERE PLACED ON THE GROUND BENEATH THE TRAILER. IDEM, COLUMBUS F D (HAZMAT), LEPC ON SCENE (OBSERVANCE ONLY). A SECOND CARGO TANK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED BACK INTO RECEIVING CARGO TANK. LEAKING CARGO TANK IS TO BE PERMANENTLY PLACED OUT OF SERVICE DUE TO AGE AND CONDITION.

REPUBLIC REFINING USES AN AUTOMATED SCALE LOADING SYSTEM. THE SYSTEM CUTS OFF THE LOADING VALVE WHEN A PRE-SET GROSS WEIGHT IS REACHED. DSI DRIVER MITCHELL TURNER SPOTTED HIS TRACTOR/TRAILER ON THE SCALES WITH ONE STEERING TIRE JUSTS LIGHTLY OFF THE SCALE. THIS GAVE A FALSE READING, THUS THE LOADING VALVE DID NOT SHUT OFF. THE TANK OVERFILLED; DRIVER TURNER MANUALLY CUT THE FLOW OFF. APPROXIMATELY 3200 LBS. OF SULFUR SPILLED.  THE MATERIAL SOLIDIFIED ON CONCRETE AND WAS CLEANED UP. THE SOLID MATERIAL WILL BE REMELTED AND USED AGAIN. THIS DRIVER WAS RETAINED IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

TRUCK AND TWO TRAILERS WERE STOPPED ON A 8% GRADE.  DRIVER SET AIR BREAKS. ROAD SURFACE WAS ICY-SNOW PACKED.  DRIVER EXITED TRUCK TO EXAMINE TRAILERS WHEN DRIVER REACHED THE REAR MOST TRAILER, THE TRUCK AND TRAILERS MOVED BACKWARD (SLIDE/ROLL) AND REAR MOST TRAILER JACK KNIFED INTO SEMI. THIS COLLISION CAUSED REAR MOST TRAILER TO BECOME UNHOOKED.  THIS UNIT WENT OFF THE ROAD, ROLLED AND IGNIGHTED.  THE FIRE CONSUMED THE TRAILER AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER.  DRIVER FAILED TO ADEQUATELY SECURE TRUCK BY PUTTING TRUCK INTO GEAR.

column168: AT APPROX. 9:00 DRIVER ENTERED TRUCK STOP FUELING AREA.  WHILE CONDUCTING VEHICLE WALK AROUND, DRIVER DISCOVERED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM TRAILER REAR DOOR.  CONTAINMENT MATERIALS CARRIED ON BOARD WERE PUT IN PLACE, LOCAL FIRE DEPATEMENT AND PA. DER WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  FCI EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WERE DISPATCHED TO SCENE. APPROX 45 GALLONS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN TRAILER, APPROX 5 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE FUEL PAD. THE PARCEL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON BROWN BELT.  IT WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN A SPILL TUB AND TRANSFERRED TO P.S.C AREA. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM COAST TO COAST ANALYTICAL LOCATED AT 7726 MOLLER RD IN INDIANAPOLIS, IN. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. THE CONTAINERS FORM COAST TO COAST WERE BEING TRANSFERRED IN TO ANOTHER VAN TRAILER. DURING THIS OPERATION, THE FORK-LIFT BEING USED TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER OF THE CONTAINERS PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER USED TO TRANSPORT THE MATERIAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED ON THE SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR THE USE OF FORK LIFTS WHEN LOADING OR OFF-LOADING VAN TRAILERS.

UPON ARIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTOM SEAM OF 2 CONTAINERS HAD DEVELEOPED A MINOR LEAK RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE 2 CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, A DOCKMAN DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE SEEPING FROM THE BUNG ON A PLASTIC DRUM. THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO THE NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MASKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A DOCKMAN DISCOVERED SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD. INSPECTION DISCOVERED ONE STEEL DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. THE STEEL DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED. THE SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP. THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, ONE FIBERBOARD CARTON WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE CARTON WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. INSPECTION FOUND ONE PLASTIC BOTTLE CRUSHED. THE CARTON WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED. THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, ONE FIBERBOARD CARTON WAS DISCOVERED WET. THE CARTON WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE CARTON. THE CARTON WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED AND DISPOSED OF AT A CERTIFIED LANDFILL.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A DOCKMAN FOUND A PLASTIC PAIL LEAKING. THE PAIL WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY. UPON INSPECTION, A PLASTIC PAIL WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE CAP. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE PAIL PROPERLY RECOOPERED. THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

AS DRIVER STOPPED AT STOPLIGHT IN ROCKVILLE IN. A TOWN POLICEMAN NOTICED PRODUCT COMING OUT OF DRAIN HOSES OFF OF THE SPLASH BOX. OFFICER PULLED DRIVER OVER.  ASORBANT WAS POURED UNDER THE DRAIN HOSES TO CONTAIN ANY PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE HOSES. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH LILLY TRANSPORTATION COORDINATOR WHO ALSO CALLED THE LILLY REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE REP.  BOTH RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE PROBLEM WAS IDENTIFIED AS A LOOSE TRI-CLOVER CLAMP HOLDING A BLANK AND GASKET IN PLACE ON THE END OF A LINE IN THE SPLASH BOX. REPAIR WAS MADE BEFORE MOVING LOAD TO DESTINATION. SPLASH BOX AND DRAIN HOSES CLEANED OF ANY PRODUCT AT DESTINATION. DRAIN LINES HAD BEEN PLUGGED TO PREVENT PRODUCT LOSS. TRAILER WAS SENT TO SHOP AND PERMANENT PIPING HAS BEEN INSTALLED. TRI-CLOVER CLAMPS REMOVED.

THESE DRUMS APPARENTLY WERE PUSHED HARD INTO THE TRAILER; THE SEPARATION CAUSED THEM TO LEAK. USING GLOVES AND GOGGLES, SUPERVISOR CONTAINED LEAKING DRUM IN AN OVERPACK AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE FOR SALVAGE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE WITH PRODUCT PUMP MOUNTED ON TRAILER. HE UNLOADED ONE COMPARTMENT OK. WHEN HE WAS ON THE SECOND COMPARTMENT THE PUMP STARTED LEAKING AROUND SHAFT. HE TIGHTENED UP NUTS AND LEAKING STOPPED, BUT WHEN HE WENT TO THE THIRD COMPARTMENT THERE WAS PRODUCT IN THE HOSE WHICH HE SPILLED. WHILE PUMPING OFF THE FOURTH COMPARTMENT THE PUMP STARTED LEAKING AGAIN. HE TIGHTENED NUTS AGAIN AND STOPPED THE LEAKING. WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THE FOURTH COMPARTMENT HE AGAIN SPILLED SOME PRODUCT FROM HOSE.  THE SAME WHEN HE DISCONNECTED HOSE AFTER FINISHING COMPARTMENT FIVE. WHEN THE TRAILER GOT BACK TO SIDNEY THE PUMP WAS REBUILT. WESTERN COOPERATIVE CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT AFTER THE PUMP STARTED LEAKING HE SHOULD HAVE SHUT DOWN AND EITHER CALLED THE TERMINAL OR MADE SOME ARRANGEMENTS TO CATCH THE SPILL IN A BUCKET AND NOT JUST LET IT LEAK ONTO CONCRETE.

LOST MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. DRUM WAS FLIPPED ON TO SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LOSS AND PLUGGED AND PATCHED. column168: 1T APPROXIMATELY 0210 HOURS THE NIGHT GUARD NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE TRAILER. HE CHECKED THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT A MARINO BAG OF MATERIAL WAS SMOLDERING. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL MANAGER BY PHONE. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED. AFTER ASSESSING THE SITUATION, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REMOVED THE TARP FROM THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO DOUSE THE MATERIAL WITH FOAM AND WATER. IN THE PROCESS OF FIGHTING THE FIRE, APPROXIMATELY 600 POUNDS OF MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE GROUND. OUR SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0500 HOURS AND BEGAN CLEAN UP. TWO DAYS WERE SPENT REMEDIATING THE SITE. A COMPANY ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT SPECIALIST TOOK 19 SOIL SAMPLES TO VERIFY THE COMPLETENESS OF THE CLEAN UP. BASED UPON THE LAB RESULTS, WE WILL DETERMINE IF ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP IS REQUIRED. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS LOADED INTO ROLL OF CONTAINERS AND HANDLED AS FOLLOWS. ONE CONTAINER WAS SENT TO THE GENERATOR FOR TESTING. TWO CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO USPCI'S TULSA, OK FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. TWO CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO ROLLINS ENVIRONMENTAL IN HOUSTON, TX FOR DISPOSAL. NOTICE WAS GIVEN TO THE NRC AND THE TEXAS TNRCC AS REQUIRED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ZALK STEEL AND SUPPLY COMPANY LOCATED AT 446 SAINT ANTHONY BLVD. IN MINNEAPOLIS, MN. TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC.  LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED ON THE SIDE OF 2 OF THE OCNTAINERS RELEASING APPROXIMTELY 1 POINT OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 2-3 OUNCES OF THIS MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT WHERE IT WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE 2 CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRYL.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.
DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE HOSE FITTING TO FILL LINE FITTING.

column168: (A & B) ON FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 19, 1993 WITH THE SAME LOAD, ANOTHER LEAK WAS DISCOVERED WHILE THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT THE SUGAR HILL RESTAURANT AND TRUCKSTOP.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER THEN CONTACTED DISPATCH WHO IN TURN CONTACTED LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TG), INC. IN ROEBUCK, SOUTH CAROLINA TO RESPOND TO CLEAN-UP SPILL.  LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER THE SITUATION AT 18:00.  AFTER ENTERING TRAILER THEY DISCOVERED THAT (2) TWO DRUMS WERE LEAKING AT THIS POINT. THEY OVERPACKED THE TWO DRUMS.  ONE DRUM CONTAINED "NITRIC ACID" AND THE OTHER DRUM CONTAINED "HYDROCHLORIC ACID".  AFTER OVERPACKING THE (2) TWO DRUMS THEY PUT VERMICULITE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL. LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TG), INC. HAD DONE EVERY THING THAT THEY WERE EQUIPPED TO DO.  THE DRIVER THEN WAITED ON THE TEAM FROM LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. TO GET THERE.  (C) AT APPROXIMATELY 22:00 LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SCENE. LAIDLAW (TS), SPILL TEAM TALKED TO THE DRIVER AND DECIDED TO ENTER THE TRAILER AND CHECK IT OUT TO BE SURE THAT THERE WERE NO MORE LEAKING CONTAINERS.  AFTER LAIDLAW (TS), TEAM ENTERED THEY FOUND THAT A DRUM OF "BENZOYL ALCOHOL" HAD A SMALL HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  THE LAIDLAW (TS) TEAM OVERPACKED THIS DRUM ADN REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED DIRT FROM UNDER THE TRAILER WHERE THE MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT.  AFTER CLEAN-UP OF ALL MATERIAL THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO THE LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. FACILITY.  SPILL SUMMARY - THERE WERE (4) DRUMS OF MATERIAL THAT WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING ON THIS ONE TRIP.  ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED TO CONTAIN LEAKING DRUMS.

column168: THE CONDUCTOR & BRAKEMAN ON YARD JOB Y222-23 IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD AT WILMINGTON, DE. EXPERIENCED SOME MINOR EYE AND THROAT IRRITATION AND NAUSEA AS THEY WORKED NEAR A CUT OF CARS CONTAINING, INCLUDING 2 RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED HAZ MATS.  BECAUSE OF ONE OF THE HAZ MATS CARS WAS RESIDUE HCN CAR, ESXT'S HAZ MAT GROUP RESPONDED AS IF THERE COULD POSSIBLY BE A RELEASE FROM THE HCN CAR.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED AND ALL OPERATIONS IN THE YARD WERE STOPPED.  DUPONT, THE SHIPPER OF THE HCN CAR, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED FROM THEIR DEEP WATER N.J. FACILITY.  THE 2 CREWMAN WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL EXAMINED AND RELEASED. DUPONT'S HAZMAT TEAM DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE FROM THE HCN CAR.  HOWEVER, THEY FOUND THE OTHER CAR HAD A DEFECTIVE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND THE ORIFICE PLUGGED. THE VALVE WAS GIVEN TO THE FRA INSPECTOR.

SWITCH CREW REPORTED A TANK CAR THAT WAS WET DOWN THE SIDES AT CSXT RAIL YARD IN RIVERDALE IL.  THE TRAIN MASTER INSPECTED THE CAR AND CONFIRMED THAT PRODUCT HAD SLOSHED FROM THE TOP. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR OHM CORP. TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE CAR. OHM FOUND THAT 3 OF 4 MANWAY LID SECUREMENT BOLTS HAD BEEN SHEARED OFF AND THE MANWAY LID HINGE WAS DAMAGED OHM CALLED GENERAL AMERICAN TANK TO LOOK AT THE CAR TO MAKE REPAIRS. GENERAL AMERICAN COULD NOT REPAIR CAR UNDER LOAD. OHM TRANSFERRED PRODUCT INTO TANK CAR ACFX 88274 ON 11/22/93.  THE DAMAGED CAR WILL BE FORWARDED TO GENERAL AMERICAN FOR REPAIRS.

AT ABOUT 1300 HOURS UPRR MGR OF MECH MAINTENANCE JIM OSBURN DETECTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS STANDING AT THE UPRR RIPTRACK AREA OF AVONDALE, LA.  OSBURN INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A SMALL VAPOR LEAK COMING FROM THE AIR INLET VALVE.  THE AIR INLET VALVE PLUG WAS LOOSE AND OSBURN TIGHTENED SAME.  THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING. OSBURN ALSO NOTED THAT ONE OF THE MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS WAS LOOSE. THIS TO WAS TIGHTENED.  OSBURN THEN NOTIFIED REGIONAL MGR OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, T. M. ROBINSON.  ROBINSON CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR AL STORZ OF ROHM & HAAS.  STORZ WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT  AND STATED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH PLANT PERSONNEL AT KNOXVILLE, TN. ON THURSDAY 11/4/93.

column168: WHILE AT THE UPRR YARD AT ADDIS, LA, THIS CAR WAS INSPECTED BY DOT-FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR, MR WM A FERNAU.  FERNAU'S INSPECTION REVEALED A SMALL VENTING OF VAPOR PRESSURE FROM THE CAR.  THE VAPORS WERE VENTING FROM AROUND THE OPERATING STEM OF THE TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. FERNAU NOTIFIED UPRR MGR OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, GREG SHORT, AND UPRR REGIONAL MGR OF CHEM TRANSP T M ROBINSON.  SHORT AND ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THA THE OPERATING STEM COULD BE TURNED, THREE REVOLUTIONS.  ADDISTIONALLY THE PACKING RETAINER NUT WAS TIGHTENED ONE HALF TURN.  ADDITIONALLY THE PACKING RETAINER NUT WAS TIGHTENED ONE HALF TURN.  THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM VENTING.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND DELIVERED TO GEORGIA GULF AT ALLEMANIA THE SAME EVENING.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR WAYNE PIPPIN OF STONE CONTAINER AT PANAMA CITY, FL.  PIPPIN, THE CHEMICAL COORDINATOR FOR STONE CONTAINER WAS ADVISED OF THE FRA INSPECTION AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN BY UPRR.  IN ADDITION, ROBINSON CONTACTED MR THURMAN BELL, TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR FOR GEORGIA GULF AT ALLEMANIA, LA.  BELL WAS ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTIONS NOTED BY FERNAU AND THE POSSIBLE NEED FOR MAINTENANCE OF THE PACKING AROUND THE STEM. ROBINSON ALSO ADVISED BELL THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE APPEARED TO BE INOPERATIVE.  IT SEEMED TO BE CLOGGED WITH DRYED CAUSTIC.  BELL WOULD SEE THAT CORRECTIVE MEASURES WERE COMPLETED BEFORE THE CAR IS RELOADED.

CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MR TOM FLORES ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 25439 AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

REGIONAL MR DEAL L WHITELEY, WAS NOTIFIED BY ACCOUNTS MGR LESLIE LACROSS, HOLMAN TRANSFER, THAT DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID, MOVING BOXCAR MP 267587, ON SPOT THEIR WAREHOUSE, WERE DAMAGED AND SPILLED SOME PRODUCT. INSPECTION DEVELOPED DRUMS WERE STACKED TWO HIGH MOVING BEHIND INTERIOR BULKHEAD DOORS.  APPEARED CAR HAD BEEN ROUGH HANDLED ACCOUNT SOME OF REMOVEABLE HEAD STEEL DRUMS WERE CRUSHED WHICH CAUSED REMOVEABLE HEADS TO COME OPEN SPILLING SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO CONTAINER AND DAMAGED DRUMS WILL BE PLACED IN OVERPACKS.  CHEMTREC WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 25449.

column168: MGR C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH WHILE MAKING TANKCAR INSPECTIONS IN THE OGDEN YARD FOUND TANKCAR UTLX12416 TO BE LEAKING, FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER TO BE LOOSE, ALL SWING BOLTS LITTLE MORE THAN FINGER TIGHT.  CAR WAS OPENED AND INSPECTED, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE GASKET WAS MISAPPLIED AS WELL.  TWO GASKETS WERE FOUND, AN OLD AND A NEW. THE CAR WAS THEN SECURED, USING 36" PIPE WRENCH AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND INCIDENT NUMBER 25619 ASSIGNED.

MARVIN MILLER, OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED IN WHITE SPRINGS, FLORIDA.

column168: ONE 11/19/93 AT APPROX. 7PM, A TRAIN CREW NOTICED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  REEDER RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR DRIPPING ABOUT 5 DROPS PER MIUNTE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE CAP SEEMED TIGHT.  SOMEONE HAD WRAPPED TEFLON TAPE ON THE OUTLET THREADS.  REEDER TIGHTENED THE CAP AND SLOWED THE LEAK BUT, DID NOT STOP IT.  CAULKING COMPOUND WAS USED AROUND THE THREADS TO FINALLY STOP THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS ASKED TO INSPECT THE VALVE BEFORE RELOADING THE CAR.

column168: ONE 11/20/93 AT APPROX. 145 PM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM DAVE BURNS, MTO AT LLOYD YARD, SPRING, TEXAS.  HE STATED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING AGAIN.  REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED.  IT WAS A BS&B 100# TYPE.  THIS CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A BAFFLE TYPE SURGE PROTECTOR.  A REPLCEMENT DISC WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR RELEASED.  SINCE THE DISC HAD FAILED TWICE IN SUCH A SHORT TIME, BURNS GAVE INSTRUCTIONS THAT THE CAR WAS NOT TO BE CUT OFF IN MOTION UNTIL IT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE OR CONNECTING ROAD.

WE HAD TWO BOXES OF POISON ON THE DOCK WAITING TO LOAD TO FMF. WHEN DAVID WHETMORE (SUP.) TOLD THE (CHECKER) BERT GEATHERS TO LOAD THE FREIGHT HE PICKED UP THE BOX AND THE SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS BAD AND ONE BOTTLE CAME OUT OF THE BOX AND BROKE.
CHECKER / LOADER GARY HOLMES PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADES. RESIDUE WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY ARR.

ON NOVEMBER 4, 1993, AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, OUR DRIVER (ROBERT CUNNINGHAM) CONTACTED OUR OFFICE TO ADVISE THAT A DRUM CONTAINING "DICHLOROMETHANE, 6.1, UN1573" HAD BEEN PUNCTURED DURING TRANSIT. CUNNINGHAM HAD CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, PACKAGE CHEMICAL.  PACKAGE CHEMICAL ADVISED THAT WE CONTACT CHEMTREC.  THIS WAS DONE.  THE LADY AT CHEMTREC ADVISED CUNNINGHAM TO NOTIFY THE CITY OF CAMBRIDGE'S FIRE DEPARTMENT. THIS WAS DONE AND THEY IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE LEAKING WAS CONTAINED AND THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ONTO ANY PUBLIC AREAS.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVER-PAK DRUM AND SEALED.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS CONTACTED BUT REFUSED TO RESPOND.  ALL MATERIALS WHICH HAD BEEN EFECTED BY THIS INCIDENT WERE PLACED IN CONTAINERS AND SEALED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REPRESENTATIVE THEN DECLARED THE VEHICLE "ENVIRONMENTALLY SAFE".  THIS ALLOWED CUNNINGHAM TO RETURN TO THE TERMINAL.  ROBERT DESCHENES HAD NUMEROUS CONVERSATIONS WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF THE CAMBRIDGE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM CLEAN HARBORS.  UPON RETURN OF THE HASHUA MOTOR EXPRESS DRIVER TO THE TERMINAL, ALL THE MATERIAL EFFECTED BY THIS INCIDENT WERE IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN A SECURE AREA OF THE TERMINAL.
THE SPILL WHICH WAS DISCOVERED INPD2 WAS BROUGHT TO PSC BY FIRST RESPONDER.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY IMPROPER PACKAGING OF GLASS BOTTLES. THE SPILL WAS PROCESSED BY THE HAZARDOUS DAMAGE PROCEDURE.

column168: V11 & V111 ABOVE: NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED. OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 1500 GALLONS OF UNLEADED MID GRADE GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE STORE, OUR DRIVER TOOK STICK READINGS FROM THE BELOW GROUND STORAGE TANK AND REALIZED THAT ONLY ABOUT 900 GALLONS OF THE 1500 HE BROUGHT WAS GOING TO FIT IN THE TANK. OUR DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD THE GAS THEN STARTED TO GET ANOTHER HOSE OFF HIS TRAILER TO BEGIN UNLOADING THE REGULAR UNLEADED GAS FOR THAT STORE. WHEN THE MID-GRADE TANK FILLED TO THE TOP TO AN UNUSED CAP TO THE TANK BLEW OFF AND ALLOWED GAS TO RUN OUT THE PARKING LOT AND DOWN THE CURBING OF THE ROAD. OUR DRIVER FINALLY SMELLED THE GAS AND NOTICED THE SPILL. HE THEN STOPPED THE FLOW OF GAS AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. SAND WAS SPREAD ON THE GASOLINE AND IT WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENT CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND OVERSAW THE CLEANUP. THEIR REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 9310389.  THIS DRIVER HAS BEEN DISMISSED FOR NOT MONITORING THE DELIVERY. CERTIFIED #9 026 532 399

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS IN OUR DANGEROUS GOODS STAGING AREA TO BE INSPECTED WHEN ODORS WERE FOUND TO BE COMING FROM THE BOX. THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND THE INNER PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THERE WAS A WHITE STYROFOAM STABILIZER IN THE BOX THAT HAD MELTED WHEN IT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE METHYL ISOBUTYL KETONE. BRAIN KENNEDY COMPLAINED OF NAUSEA. JAN LITTLE WAS NAUSEATED AND DROWSY, AND CHARLENE KUNZ SAID SHE WAS LIGHTHEADED. ALL WERE DUE TO THE ODORS IN THE BOX. THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED TO A WELL VENTILATED AREA. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND MANDATED TO PICK UP THE FREIGHT FROM FEDEX.
TWO CANS HAD LOOSE CLOSURES. ALL CLOSURES WERE CHECKED AND COMPLETE PACKAGE OVERPACKED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

ON 11-10-93, SORT SUPERVISOR, DAN MCCULLOM, REPORTED A SHIPMENT OUTSIDE THE MAIN SORT THAT WAS LEAKING. THIS SHIPMENT HAD FALLEN OFF A CUSHMAN. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, FOUND THIS SHIPMENT SITTING ON THE GROUND. THIS WAS A METAL, FRICTION TYPE RECEPTICLE. THIS WAS A SINGLE TYPE PACKAGE THAT HAS A CAPACITY OF FIVE GALLONS. THIS RECEPTICLE CONTAINED "RUST BAN 392". THIS MATERIAL HAD THE CONSISTANCY OF OIL. ON THE SIDE OF THIS METAL RECEPTICLE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. UPON READING THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET IT SHOWED THE FLASH POINT OF THE MATERIAL TO BE 100 DEGREES F. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT, IN A RECOVERY DRUM, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

BE ADVISED THAT THE ILN HAZMAT DISPATCH RECEIVED A CALL VIA RADIO FROM GROUND 29 (BILL VANPELT) THAT HE HAD A SPILL ON THE PUSH OFF BELT IN "A" BUILDING, OF OUR SORT FACILITY, ON THE PROPERTY OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. HE STATED THAT THE BELT WAS DOWN, AND HE HAD 1 EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT. THIS SPILL HAD THE ODOR OF VARNISH. 0058. THE BELT WAS UP AT 0101 AND THE RESPONSE TEAM WAS CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 0125. CERT 10 (ADDIE CAMPTON) ILN PART-TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN AND CERT 13 (JEFFREY A. HOSTETLER) ILN HAZ MAT COORDINATOR INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A MAHOGANY STAIN, APPROX. 1 GAL HAD BEEN LOST ONTO THE BELT AND FLOOR. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND TAKEN BY MYSELF TO THE HAZ MAT DEPT. FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. DESCRIPTION OF THE OUTER CONTAINERS AS FOLLOWS: TOP: NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. FRONT: NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. RIGHT SIDE: NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. BACK: NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. BOTTOM: MANUFACTURER SEAL: HARTFORD CONTAINER INC., WEST HARTFORD, CONN. BURST 200, COMB: 84, SIZE LIMIT: 75, GROSS WT:65.  THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS SECURED WITH CLEAR PACKAGING WRAP. THE AIRWAY BILL WAS ATTACHED TO THE WRAP AND WAS ILLEGIBLE DUE TO THE STAIN THAT HAD ESCAPED THE INNER RECEPTICLE. INNER CONTAINER AS FOLLOWS:1 X 1 GALLON METAL CONTAINER WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE. BOX 2 OR 2 DESCRIPTION AS FOLLOWS: SAME AS BOX 1 ABOVE. THESE 2 META; AEROSOL CONTAINERS WERE SECURED TOGETHER BY CLEAR PACKAGING WRAP. STATED: TONE FINISH #102-0420 CLEAR GLOSS LACQUER, EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE, CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, VAPORS HARMFUL, CAUSES NOSE, THROAT AND SKIN IRRITATION. THERE WERE NO LABELS, MARKINGS, OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DOCUMENTATION ON OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT IS LOCATED IN TEH ILN HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION.

ON 11-9-93, RAMP AREA MANAGER, JEANNE DONAHUE, CALLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPATCH AND ADVISED US THAT FLIGHT 151 INBOUND WAS DETECTING AN ODOR ON THE MAIN FLIGHT DECK. THE AIRCRAFT WAS DUE IN AT 0030. I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS, RESPONDED TO GATE B-113 AND AWAITED THE ARRIVAL OF FLIGHT 151. ONCE THE AIRCRAFT BLOCKED ITS GATE, I TOOK THE GAS DETECTION INSTRUMENT TO THE MAIN CARGO DECK TO CHECK FOR ANY ABNORMAL READINGS. THERE WERE NONE OBSERVED. I BOARDED THE AIRCRAFT AND DETECTED A FLAMMABLE TYPE ODOR. I ASKED THE FLIGHT CREW TO EXIT THE AIRCRAFT UNTIL WE DETERMINED WHAT WAS CAUSING THE ODOR. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS, AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, NEAL VAN SAUN, DONNED STRUCTURAL FIRE FIGHTING GEAR AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS TO OFF-LOAD THE UNIT LOAD DEVICES. IN THE FIRST UNIT LOAD DEVICE OFF THE AIRCRAFT WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING THE FLAMMABLE TYPE ODOR. ONCE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS OPENED WE FOUND INSIDE A FIVE GALLON CAPACITY, STEEL DRUM THAT WAS LYING ON ITS SIDE. THIS STEEL DRUM CONTAINED A "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (METHYL ETHYL KETONE AND ISOPROPANOL)". THERE WAS POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE FAILED ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO LEAK INSIDE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE. THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: MECHANICAL DEPT. EMPLOYEE NOTED VAPOR RELEASE FROM TOP OF TANK CAR. INSPECTION BY SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DECHANT, UPRR, DISCLOSED PRIMARY LEAK WAS FROM GAUGING ROD AREA. VALVE WAS FOUND OPEN 3/8 TURN, WITH PORT PLUG INSTALLED. LIQUID WAS OBSERVED RISING AROUND VALVE STEM; RUNOFF CONTAINED INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THAT LEAK STOPPED COMPLETELY 1830 HRS UPON FULL CLOSURE OF VALVE. AN ADDITIONAL VAPOR RELEASE WAS AUDIBLE INSIDE THE HOUSING; HOWEVER, EXACT SOURCE COULD NOT BE IMMEDIATELY DETERMINED DUE TO PRESENCE AND VAPORIZATION OF LIQUID STILL PRESENT FROM THE PRIMARY RELEASE. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND ALLOWED TO SIT OVERNIGHT TO ALLOW VAPORIZATION AND DISSPIPATION OF PRODUCT RESIDUE. INSPECTION AT 0845 HRS 11/15 DISCLOSED SLIGHT LEAK PRESENT AT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, AROUND THE O-RING RETAINER. INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS GAUGED AT 140 PSI (VALVE SETTING 223PSI), INDICATING LEAKAGE MOST LIKELY DUE TO A FAULTY OR IMPROPERLY INSTALLED O-RING. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING CONDITION OF THE VALVE, AND AS AN ALTERNATIVE TO FIELD REPLACEMENT OF THE O-RING OR A FIELD TRANSFER, IT WAS AGREED THAT THE SAFEST COURSE OF ACTION WOULD BE TO MOVE THE RAILCAR TO A NEARBY FACILITY FOR COMPLETE UNLOADING AND DEPRESSURIZATION THEN SUBSEQUENTLY DIVERTED AND UNLOADED LOCALLY AND MAYWOOD COOP, NORTH PLATTE.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTAION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DON ERTLE, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR TGOX 21000 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR BY THE CREW ON THE YARD SWITCH ENGINE. THE CAR ARRIVED YERMO AT 1600 HOURS, NOVEMBER 14, 1993, MOVING IN TRAIN HKYR-11. THE CAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND SET TO YARD TRACK #19 AND ISOLATED PENDING INVESTIGATION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON OSECO DISC. THE REMAINING VALVE AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT CARL ZERWECK WAS CALLED BY YARDMASTER KNOWLTON AT THE CREST REGARDING TANK CAR UTLX80023 REPORTED LEAKING AT THE WEST END OF CENTENNIAL YARD, TRACK 202. ZERWECK FOUND THE CAR DIRECTLY UNDER MO-PAC BRIDGE. THE CAR CONTAINED ETHYLENE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, UN1083, FLAMMABLE LIQUID. THE FT. WORTH FIRE DEPARTMENT,  BATTALION CHIEF T.L. MATHEWS IN CHARGE, WAS ON THE SCENE AS WAS EMTECH. BUTCH BEARDSLEY WITH EMTECH AND MYSELF APPROACHED THE CAR WITH THE FIRE DEPT. PROVIDING BACKUP. WE REMOVED INTACT SEAL REXENE 593182 FROM THE HASP ON THE VALVE HOUSING CABINET. WE FOUND THE ACME KNOCK TIGHT CAP VERY LOOSE AND PRODUCT DRIPPING. APPROXIMATELY FIVE TURNS WERE NEEDED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP. APPARENTLY THE VALVE WAS NOT SEALED AS WE WERE ABLE TO SNUG THE VALVE WHEEL AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE PRODUCT STENCIL ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR WERE COVERED WITH DUCT TAPE AND THE TAPE WAS REMOVED. THE FT. WORTH FIRE DEPARTMENT MADE AN EVACUATION OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA THAT LASTED APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS. THE CAR WAS REPAIRED AT APPROXIMATELY 1210 HOURS AND NORMAL ACTIVITIES WERE RESUMED.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: TRAILER 511-5131 ARRRIVED UOA (OAKLAND SERVICE CENTER) AT 0930/19.  MIKE GUSMAN WAS BREAK-OUT PERSON.  TRALIER PLACARDED DANGEROUS/OXIDIZER, 22 BILLS/ 98%/ 18,514lbs.  MIKE UNLOADED PRO 268-204322, CALLED FOR 67 CNTS ON 1 PALLET, PLUS 4 LOOSE.  4 LOOSE IN CORROSIVE.  BREAKOUT 1 SWP PLUS 3 LOOSE.  CARDBOARD AND PLYBOARD WERE FOUND ON FLOOR, FOUND MY MIKE GUSMAN (TO COVER SPILL?)  OBVIOUSLY 1 BOX WAS DAMAGED AT ORGIN, AND SPILLED IN TRAILER, WITHOUT PROPER CLEANING OF SPILL-JUST COVERED UP.  THE 3 BOXES WERE ALSO CONTAMINATED AND SENT OUT.  UNLOADER TOOK THE 3 BOXES AND OUT ON CART AND NOTICED HIS HANDS BURNING AND WENT TO SUPERVISOR.  THIS SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN HELD AT ORGIN UNTIL IT WAS RECOUPED.

ON 11/08/93, AT 3:00 PM, I RUBEN SALAZAR, CITY DRIVER FOR THE DRT TERMINAL, WAS DELIVERING FREIGHT AT BASLER ELECTRIC CO., 366 PIERCE, EAGLE PASS, TEXAS.  I HAD 3 DRUMS OF XYLENES 3 UN1307 PGIII APPLIED ON PRO 0084515852.  MR. LEO LONGORIA, WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR AT BASLER ELECTRIC , WAS UNLOADING THE DRUMS INDIVIDUALLY WITH HIS FORKLIFT.  WHILE ENTERING THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD THE SECOND DRUM, THE BLADE ON THE FORKLIFT WAS ABOUT 3 INCHES FROM THE FLOOR AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM, MAKING A HOLE ABOUT 3 INCHES LONG AND 1 INCH WIDE IN THE BOTTOM OF DRUM.  THE DRUM BEGAN TO LEAK CONTENTS.  BOTH LEO AND I DECIDED TO FLIP THE DRUM OVER TO SALAVGE SOME OF THE CONTENTS IN THE DRUM.  WHILE LAYING THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE, A LARGE STREAM OF THE LIQUID SQUIRTED OUT AND FELL ON MR. LONGORIA'S HEAD AND FACE.  HE BEGAN TO COMPLAIN OF A BURNING SENSATION ON HIS NOSE AND EYES, AND RAN TO THE BATHROOM TO RINSE HIS FACE.  I, THEN, CALLED 911 AND REPORTED THAT AN EMPLOYEE HAD HAD CONTACT WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID TO HIS FACE, AND 911 CONTACTED THE PARAMEDICS AND FIRE DEPARTMENT IN EAGLE PASS. AT THE TIME, I CALLED JOEL RAMOS, TERMINAL MANAGER OF THE DRT TERMINAL, AND EXPLAINED TO HIM WHAT HAD HAPPEN.  HE TOLD ME TO REPORT BACK AFTER I FOUND OUT MORE ABOUT MR. LONGORIA'S SITUATUIN.   WHEN THE PARAMEDICS ARRIVED, THEY FLUSHED MR. LONGORIA'S FACE AND EYES WITH A SOLUTION AND DECIDED TO TAKE HIM TO THE HOSPITAL FOR MORE OBSERVATIONS.  I THEN CALLED TOM KOHLBRECKER, PLANT MANAGER OF BASLER ELECTRIC IN PIEDRAS NEGRAS, MEXICO, AND EXPLAINED TO HIM THAT MR. LONGORIA HAD BEEN IN AN ACCIDENT AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND SOMEONE NEEDED TO TAKE OVER THE WAREHOUSE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND ASKED ME QUESTIONS ON THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM.  THEN THEY NOTICED THAT ONLY 1 TO 1 1/2 GALLONS HAD SPLIT FROM THE TRAILER DOWN ONTO A PUDDLE OF WATER THAT HAD ACCUMILATED ON THE SLOPED DOCK AREA.  AFTER REMOVING THE DRUM, AND PLACING IT ON A CRADDLE THEY MADE OUT OF LUMBER, THEY ASKED TOM KOHLBRECKER TO PURCHASE SOME TO POUR OVER THE WATER/CHEMICAL MIXTURE AND TO CALL THE CITY OF EAGLE PASS TO GET INSTRUCTIONS AS TO HOW TO DISPOSE OF THE SOAKED UP MIXTURE.  TOM RECEIVED THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT AND TOLD ME THAT I COULD LEAVE.  IT WAS MY FINAL DELIVERY.  I THEN RETURNED TO THE DRT TERMINAL IN DEL RIO.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 11/20/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 2335 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS HAZ MAT COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR., INC. 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT EMITTING A STRONG ODOR. THE SHIPMENT WAS IN THE BELLY OF AIRCRAFT 956 AX PARKED AT GATE A23 AT THE SAME LOCATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS AFFIXED, NOR WERE THERE ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THE SHIPMENT.  INSIDE THIS FIRBRBOARD BOX I FOUND MISC. AIRCRAFTS PARTS ALL WRAPPED IN BUBBLE PACK. THERE WAS ALSO 1X1 GALLON METAL CAN WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE. THIS METAL CAN WAS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE PACK AND THE CLOSURE WAS TAPED FOR POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE IT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FROM THE SHIPPER ON THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE METAL CAN. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET THAT WAS RECEIVED INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THE SHIPMENT IS NOW BEING HELD FOR INVESTIAGION BY THE FAA. UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA, THE SHIPMENT WILL BE REPACKED IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AS THE CONSIGNEE IS OUTSIDE THE CONTINENTAL US.

ON THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 1993 A DRIVER FOR BRYSON INDUSTRIAL SERVICES, INC. DISCOVERED THAT THE 48FT. BOX VAN TRAILER THAT HE WAS TRANSPORTING HAD AN UNKNOWN TYPE OF MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY THE VAN WAS LOCATED AT THE RYDER SHOP IN KNOXVILLE, TN.  THE DRIVER PULLED THE TRUCK TO AN ISOLATED AREA AT THE RYDER SHOP AND PUT SOME ABSORBANT BOOMS AND PADS DOWN TO CONTAIN/ABSORB THE MATERIAL. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED HIS DISPATCH OFFICE FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. DISPATCH IN TURN CONTACTED ALL PERSONS AS OUTLINED IN THE CONTINGENCY PLAN.  AT THIS POINT THE 24 HOUR EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS CALLED (INFOTRAC). THE CONTACT PERSON AT INFOTRAC WAS RON-RESPONDER #8.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTACT THE KNOX COUNTY RURAL METRO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 23:40 KNOX FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TOOK COMPLETE CONTROL OF THE SITUATION AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO GET BACK OUT OF THE WAY.  AFTER READING THE MANIFEST THE KNOX FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED IN THE KNOX COUNTY REGIONAL SPECIAL HAZARDOUS UNIT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 24:20 THE KNOX COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED.  AT 24:50 THE HAZMAT TEAM OPENED AND ENTERED THE TRAILER, AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES THEY CAME OUT AND SAID THEY HAD FOUND A 55 GALLON DRUM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID THAT WAS LEAKING.  THE HAZMAT TEAM WENT BACK IN THE TRAILER AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND LOOKED TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANYMORE LEAKING CONTAINERS.  AFTER THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS SATISFIED THAT THERE WERE NO MORE LEAKING THEY PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE GROUND.  THE HAZMAT TEAM SAMPLED THE GROUND AND DETERMINED THAT ALL THAT WAS NEEDED TO CLEAN THE GROUND WAS TO WASH/DILUTE WITH HIGH PRESSURE HOSE. THE BRYSON DRIVER WAS ASKED TO DO THIS TASK.  AFTER WASHING THE AREA DOWN THE BRYSON DRIVER WAS CALLED TO CONTINUE ON HIS WAY.

THE DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTACT THE KNOX COUNTY RURAL METRO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 23:40 KNOX FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TOOK COMPLETE CONTROL OF THE SITUATION AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO GET BACK OUT OF THE WAY.  AFTER READING THE MANIFEST THE KNOX FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED IN THE KNOX COUNTY REGIONAL SPECIAL HAZARDOUS UNIT. AT APPROXIMATELY 24:20 THE KNOX COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED.  AT 24:50 THE HAZMAT TEAM OPENED AND ENTERED THE TRAILER, AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES THEY CAME OUT AND SAID THEY HAD FOUND A 55 GALLON DRUM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID THAT WAS LEAKING.  THE HAZMAT TEAM WENT BACK IN THE TRAILER AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND LOOKED TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANYMORE LEAKING CONTAINERS. AFTER THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS SATISFIED THAT THERE WERE NO MORE LEAKING THEY PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE GROUND.  THE HAZMAT TEAM SAMPLED THE GROUND AND DETERMINED THAT ALL THAT AS NEEDED TO CLEAN THE GROUND WAS TO WASH/DILUTE WITH HIGH PRESSURE HOSE.  THE BRYSON DRIVER WAS ASKED TO DO THIS TASK. AFTER WASHING THE AREA DOWN THE BRYSON DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON HIS WAY.

1N THE 15TH OF NOVEMBER OUR COMPANY FUEL TRUCK WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A UNDERGROUND FUEL TANK AT 1255 E HWY 36 IN ST PAUL.  BELIEVING THE TANK TO BE ALMOST EMPTY THE DRIVER FAILED TO TAKE A STICK READING OF THE CURRENT INVENTORY. ASSUMING THE TANK TO BE EMPTY AND CAPABLE OF HOLDING THE CONTENTS OF HIS LOAD THE DRIVER WAS WALKING AROUND HIS TRUCK AND CLEANING THE INSIDE OF HIS CAB. UPON NOTICING THAT THERE WAS AN OVERFLOW OF PRODUCT THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMPING EQUIPMENT AND CONTAINED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT THE BEST HE COULD WITH FLOOR DRY AND OIL SOAK PADS CARRIED ON HIS TRUCK.  HIS NEXT STEP WAS TO NOTIFY THE OFFICE OF THE PROBLEM AT HAND. THE COMPANY FOR WHICH HE WAS FILLING THE TANK ALSO NOTICED THE OVERFLOW AND CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. THEY RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE DEPT OF PUBLIC WORKS WHO DUMPED A LOAD OF SAND ON THE OIL TO FURTHER CONTAIN THE SPREAD OF OIL AND SOAK UP ANY PUDDLED PRODUCT.  THE DOT AND MPCA HAD PEOPLE ON SITE TO EVALUATE THE RELEASE AND DETERMINE FURTHER CLEANUP NEEDS. THE SAND WAS LEFT OVERNITE AND PICKED THE FOLLOWING DAY AND SHIPPED TO C.S. MC CROSSAN INC. FOR THERMAL TREATMENT OF THE SAND. DOB DONGOSKE IS THE CONTACT AT C.S. MCCROSSAN, WHOM ARE LOCATED AT 7865 JEFFERSON HWY IN MAPLE GROVE, MN. IT WAS ESTIMATED AROUND 7865 JEFFERSON HWY IN MAPLE GROVE, MN. IT WAS ESTIMATED AROUND 5 TONS OF SAND WERE SPREAD AND SENT FOR THERMAL TREATING. THE MPCA SPILL # FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 18722. FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE WILL BE AVOIDED BY REQUIRING THE ATTENDING DRIVER TO MAKE BEFORE AND AFTER MEASUREMENTS OF THE TANK TO BE FILLED.  THE MOST IMPORTANT ASPECT IS THAT THE DRIVER WILL AS REQUIRED  BY LAW TO BE AT THE NOZZLE WHILE DISPENSING FUEL.

IN AN ATTEMPT TO RERAIL TANK CAR ACFX 89166, THE LOAD SHIFTED AND ROLLED OVER ONTO THE OUTRIGGER OF THE PETTIBONE CRANE. THE OUTRIGGER PUNCTURED A LARGE HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE CAR, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 17,000 GAL OF PRODUCT. THIS OCCURRED AT THE CENTENNIAL YARD RIP TRACK. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED OF RIP TRACK, STORE AND DIESEL SHOP PERSONNEL. THE ON-SCENE COMMAND POST WAS SET UP AT THE RIP TRACK BY DOB STEPHEN, SUPT. THE FIRE DEPT.  WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. MALONE SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE TRACY HOLLISTER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED.  MR. HOLLISTER PROVIDED THE PRODUCT INFORMATION. UPRR MTM JOHN TAYLOR AND UPRR MEM BILL CAMPBELL CHECKED THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE YARD AT THE DRAINAGE CULVERTS FOR PRODUCT. THE CULVERT DIRECTLY ACROSS FROM THE SPILL AREA HAD A STRONG ODOR AND WAS DAMMED TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE TRINITY RIVER.  THE HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER NOTIFIED THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES AND WAS INCIDENT COMMAND. TNRCC WAS NOTIFIED BY LOCAL AUTHORITY AT 2315 HRS.  EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CLALLED FOR CLEANUP AND EQUIPMENT DECON. RADIAN WAS CALLED FOR AIR MONITORING AND SOIL SAMPLING. THE WRECKING CREW WHICH WAS ON SCENE AT THE TIME OF INCIDENT WAS DECONNED AND MEDICALLY CHECKED OUT BY THE FORT WORTH AND FIRE DEPT.  THEIR CONTAMINATED CLOTHING AND GEAR WAS COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF. UPRR CASUALTY MANAGEMENT REP. SHIRLEY SEWELL ARRANGED FOR REPLACEMENT AND OR/ COMPENSATION.  VACUMMN TRUCKS COLLECTED THE STANDING PRODUCT AT THE SITE AND ALSO COLLECTED ANY PRODUCT STOPPED AT THE RIVER DAMS. UPRR EMG PERSONNEL STEVE BERKI AND MARK SCHAFER WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO FURTHER THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP. CONCRETE AREAS WERE STEAM-CLEANED, EFFECTED EQUIPMENT WAS DECONNED AND THE RUN-OFF WAS COLLECTED IN A FRAC TANK FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND COLLECTED ALSO.  RADIAN CONTINUED TO  SAMPLE AIR SOIL THROUGHOUT THE INCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY 1/3 OF THE TANK CAR LOAD REMAINED IN THE CAR.  BECAUSE OF THE FLAMMABILITY FACTOR OF THE PRODUCT, THE CAR WAS FLOODED WITH INERT GAS TO LESSEN THE THE POSSIBILTY OF SPARK WHILE UNRIGHTING THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT OR SPILLAGE. UPRR CTS REG. MANAGER BOB STINE, CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET, AND SR. SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT CARL ZERWECK PATCHED THE 3' X 3' HOLE.  CAR OWNER WILL DESIGNATE FACILITY FOR THE CLEANING AND REPAIR OF CAR.

column168: I KEVIN SELL, WAS IN AN ACCIDENT ON THE DATE OF 11-23-93. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE TRAVELING DOWN HWY 89 SOUTH BOUND. WHILE REACHING FOR A DRINK OF POP, I MUST HAVE TURNED THE STEERING WHEEL SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT, THE RIGHT FRONT STEERING TIRE DROPPED OF THE EDGE OF THE ROAD, FORCING THE REST OF THE TRUCK OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROAD DOWN ALONGSIDE THE DITCH. THE TRUCK HAD COME TO A COMPLETE STOP, WHEN THE EDGE OF THE DITCH GAVE WAY. THE RIGHT FRONT STEERING TIRE DROPPED OFF THE EDGE, CAUSING THE REST OF THE TRUCK TO FOLLOW, LAYING IT ON ITS SIDE.
